Node.Notes: Many different words differently to yield "[They have] no struggles; their bodies are healthy and strong."
Literally, "fat," which was an ancient picture of healthy prosperity.
Uncertain. Tree assumes a garment of violence wraps around them. Could also be: violence covers them like a garment (V-ADV-S-PP).
Text seems to be "their eye goes out from fatness," which could be a figure of insensitivity/unwillingness to submit to God or excessive self-indulgence.
General sense seems to be something like vain fanciess pass through their minds.
Uncertain. Often taken as vain imagination/delusion as metaphorical from established sense of image/scrupture.

Likely figurative for blasphemy against God in heaven and malicious talk against other people on earth. Maybe also a caricature picturing the speakers as giants you set their mouths in heaven and whose tongues struts through the earth.
Uncertain. "His people return here," seems to mean that God's people turn to these wealthy wicked people.
Uncertain. "Waters of abundance" is probably a full cup. Seems to mean that God's people not only turn to the rich, but unthinkingly (because desirous of their affluence) drink down their language.
Seems to be "(the wicked are) like a dream after one awakes, O Lord; when you rouse, you despise their shadows." Sense is that the wicked will last no longer than the images of a dream.
Uncertain. Could be "in the city" (as in ancient versions) instead of "when [you] arise." The text actually would fit "in the city" exactly, but most assume a contracted form of "to rouse" instead.
